so maybe I can find Darlene's sister.

1:58:18.000 --> 1:58:20.000
And maybe she can tell me
who this mystery man is.

1:58:20.000 --> 1:58:22.840
Try that. I've got to go. She's very cute.

1:58:26.714 --> 1:58:28.336
You know,

1:58:28.336 --> 1:58:31.798
it's interesting that you should mention
Zodiac calling people at home.

1:58:31.798 --> 1:58:33.336
He did that in San Francisco once.

1:58:33.336 --> 1:58:34.924
What? Who did he call?

1:58:34.924 --> 1:58:38.000
I can't tell you.
That's privileged information.

1:58:38.630 --> 1:58:40.840
But maybe Melvin Belli could.

1:58:43.462 --> 1:58:45.042
Melvin Belli.

1:58:45.924 --> 1:58:48.294
How do I get to Melvin Belli?

1:58:48.294 --> 1:58:51.420
-He should be along soon.
-Oh, that's all right.

1:58:51.420 --> 1:58:53.882
I've really...
I've only been waiting two hours, so...

1:58:53.882 --> 1:58:55.798
He's usually not this late.

1:58:55.798 --> 1:58:58.630
Oh, cookies. Thank you.
These look great.

1:58:59.420 --> 1:59:03.420
-You are here on business?
-I'm writing a book about the Zodiac.

1:59:03.420 --> 1:59:06.462
I remember that. I spoke to him.

1:59:06.462 --> 1:59:11.168
-You mean to Mr. Belli about the case?
-No, to the Zodiac when he called.

1:59:11.168 --> 1:59:14.546
He said he had to kill
because it was his birthday.

1:59:14.546 --> 1:59:17.882
He said it... Wait.
He said it was his birthday?

1:59:17.924 --> 1:59:20.462
Yes. You want something to drink?

1:59:21.462 --> 1:59:25.504
-When was this?
-Oh, so many years ago.

1:59:27.168 --> 1:59:29.840
Mr. Belli was away for Christmas.

1:59:29.840 --> 1:59:31.168
Gone for a week.

1:59:31.168 --> 1:59:33.630
The Zodiac called,
wanting to talk to him.

1:59:33.630 --> 1:59:35.420
I said, "He is not here."

1:59:35.420 --> 1:59:38.420
He said, "I have to kill.
Today is my birthday."

1:59:38.420 --> 1:59:40.462
And then he hangs up.

1:59:40.462 --> 1:59:42.042
Then the letter arrived.

1:59:42.042 --> 1:59:46.210
So, the call came
before the letter of December 20th.

1:59:46.210 --> 1:59:48.210
Mr. Belli was gone for a week?

1:59:48.210 --> 1:59:52.084
He came back on Christmas.
Not a good day to work.

1:59:52.084 --> 1:59:54.042
So, he left on the 18th.

1:59:55.210 --> 1:59:56.756
Is that helpful?

1:59:56.756 --> 1:59:58.294
She said it was his birthday.

1:59:58.294 --> 2:00:02.210
<i>Well, you'd have to confirm that,</i>
<i>now wouldn't you?</i>

2:00:02.210 --> 2:00:03.714
How?

2:00:03.714 --> 2:00:06.924
<i>Well, I never spoke to her,</i>
<i>but maybe my partner did.</i>

2:00:06.924 --> 2:00:09.840
-How do I get a hold of him?
<i>-You don't. Bill wanted out of this.</i>

2:00:09.840 --> 2:00:12.210
<i>As far as I’m concerned,</i>
<i>he should stay out.</i>

2:00:12.210 --> 2:00:13.588
How do I confirm it?

2:00:13.588 --> 2:00:16.210
<i>Well, if my partner</i>
<i>did talk to someone from Justice,</i>

2:00:16.210 --> 2:00:17.882
<i>then they would've had</i>
<i>to put that in a report.</i>

2:00:17.882 --> 2:00:20.294
<i>That's standard procedure.</i>

2:00:20.294 --> 2:00:22.462
-Okay.
<i>-Mel Nicolai.</i>

2:00:22.462 --> 2:00:24.504
-Thank you.
<i>-Goodbye.</i>

2:00:24.504 --> 2:00:26.756
I just need to confirm a date.

2:00:26.756 --> 2:00:28.210
-Mr. Graysmith...
-I've narrowed it down

2:00:28.210 --> 2:00:30.588
between the 18th and the 20th
of December, and I just need...

2:00:30.588 --> 2:00:33.966
Okay, I'll play.
Let's say this phone call did take place.

2:00:33.966 --> 2:00:35.504
Let's say it really was Zodiac.

2:00:35.504 --> 2:00:38.378
Why would he volunteer
the day he was born?

2:00:38.378 --> 2:00:40.630
Plus, nobody died on December 18th,

2:00:40.630 --> 2:00:43.504
just like nobody died over the weekend
when he was gonna kill a dozen people,

2:00:43.504 --> 2:00:45.966
or when he was gonna
shoot school kids or blow up buses.

2:00:45.966 --> 2:00:47.420
He's a liar, Mr. Graysmith.

2:00:47.420 --> 2:00:49.168
What if he made a mistake?

2:00:49.210 --> 2:00:51.336
What if he wasn't lying?
What if it was him on the phone?

2:00:51.336 --> 2:00:53.798
He didn't expect to pick it up,
a nice person to pick up.

2:00:53.798 --> 2:00:55.210
What if? What if? What if?

2:00:55.210 --> 2:00:58.672
Look, off the record,
Bill Armstrong checked this out.

2:00:58.672 --> 2:01:01.378
We took this very seriously.

2:01:01.378 --> 2:01:04.714
None of the suspects had the
same birthday as this phantom caller.

2:01:04.714 --> 2:01:06.924
Bill Armstrong.

2:01:12.462 --> 2:01:14.504
Can I give you a piece of advice?

2:01:14.504 --> 2:01:16.168
You're looking in the wrong place.

2:01:16.168 --> 2:01:19.336
Handwriting, fingerprints,
that's what this whole thing's about.

2:01:19.336 --> 2:01:20.672
Stick to the evidence.

2:01:21.714 --> 2:01:22.798
Hi.

2:01:31.084 --> 2:01:34.210
-Hey. How was your day?
-Long.

2:01:39.630 --> 2:01:41.126
Who's Sherwood Morrill?

2:01:41.126 --> 2:01:44.000
He's a handwriting expert
in Sacramento.

2:01:44.000 --> 2:01:45.210
He called.

2:01:45.210 --> 2:01:47.420
He said he can meet you
tomorrow morning at 7:00.

2:01:47.420 --> 2:01:48.798
Oh, great.

2:01:48.798 --> 2:01:51.672
-So you're taking off work?
-Just an hour.

2:01:53.420 --> 2:01:55.546
Sacramento's two hours away.

2:01:56.672 --> 2:01:58.294
-Really?
-Yes.

2:01:59.042 --> 2:02:00.672
What's this?

2:02:00.672 --> 2:02:03.378
Oh, that's that article.

2:02:03.378 --> 2:02:07.084
"Robert Graysmith has quietly been
shopping his book about the Zodiac."

2:02:07.084 --> 2:02:08.252
Yeah.

2:02:08.252 --> 2:02:11.000
It talks all about you
researching Zodiac.

2:02:11.000 --> 2:02:12.504
Well, that's what the article's about.

2:02:12.504 --> 2:02:15.042
I'm not so sure that's something
we want people to know about.

2:02:15.042 --> 2:02:16.210
Why? Are you embarrassed?

2:02:16.210 --> 2:02:19.420
Robert, what's the one thing
we know about Zodiac?

2:02:20.042 --> 2:02:21.336
He reads the Chronicle.

2:02:21.336 --> 2:02:23.882
Yeah, but he's never
gonna read Herb Caen.

2:02:28.504 --> 2:02:30.924
-Hello.
<i>-Mr. Graysmith?</i>

2:02:30.924 --> 2:02:33.588
<i>The Robert Graysmith</i>
<i>mentioned in the paper today?</i>

2:02:33.588 --> 2:02:36.714
-Yeah?
<i>-I can tell you who the Zodiac is.</i>

2:02:40.504 --> 2:02:41.630
Who is this?

2:02:41.630 --> 2:02:43.882
<i>The Zodiac Killer</i>
<i>is obsessed with movies.</i>

2:02:43.882 --> 2:02:46.672
<i>He recorded his murders on film.</i>

2:02:46.672 --> 2:02:50.126
<i>I tried to tell the police,</i>
<i>but they wouldn't follow through on it.</i>

2:02:50.126 --> 2:02:53.168
<i>There's a man you need to find.</i>
<i>His name is Bob Vaughn.</i>

2:02:53.168 --> 2:02:55.840
-Pen, pen.
<i>-V-A-U-G-H-N.</i>

2:02:55.840 --> 2:02:58.042
<i>He's a friend of the Zodiac's.</i>

2:02:58.042 --> 2:03:00.294
<i>Mr. Vaughn does not know</i>
<i>his friend is a killer,</i>

2:03:00.294 --> 2:03:03.000
<i>and he is storing</i>
<i>some film canisters for him.</i>

2:03:03.000 --> 2:03:04.798
<i>In these canisters is the evidence.</i>

2:03:04.798 --> 2:03:08.252
Okay, yeah, friend? Who is this friend?

2:03:08.252 --> 2:03:10.000
<i>You have quite enough to get started.</i>

2:03:10.000 --> 2:03:11.840
Oh, please.

2:03:11.840 --> 2:03:15.168
<i>The Zodiac's name is Rick Marshall.</i>

2:03:19.000 --> 2:03:20.882
Your toast is burning.

2:03:21.882 --> 2:03:26.924
We choose at some point in our lives
how to physically construct each letter.

2:03:27.672 --> 2:03:30.000
Once we lock that into our brains,

2:03:30.000 --> 2:03:32.378
our handwriting may change
over the years,

2:03:32.378 --> 2:03:35.168
but the moves themselves
remain unaltered.

2:03:35.168 --> 2:03:36.672
-Understand?
-Yes.

2:03:38.252 --> 2:03:40.210
Except Zodiac's doesn't.

2:03:41.798 --> 2:03:43.756
Specifically with his "K."

2:03:44.966 --> 2:03:47.966
In his first letters,
he executed the "K" with two strokes.

2:03:47.966 --> 2:03:49.546
Later letters, he did them with three.

2:03:49.546 --> 2:03:51.924
-Why?
-We don't know.

2:03:51.924 --> 2:03:53.966
Excuse me, I've got to spray this.

2:03:53.966 --> 2:03:57.168
How many suspects
were cleared through handwriting?

2:03:57.168 --> 2:03:58.714
All of them.

2:03:58.714 --> 2:04:02.294
Also the print in the cab.
No match was ever found.

2:04:02.294 --> 2:04:06.420
Is there any way that someone
could beat a handwriting test?

2:04:06.420 --> 2:04:07.504
No.

2:04:07.504 --> 2:04:10.714
Whoever the Zodiac is,
he's not someone I cleared.

2:04:11.630 --> 2:04:15.210
About a month ago, a man showed up
on my doorstep very distraught.

2:04:15.210 --> 2:04:17.294
His name was Wallace Penny.

2:04:18.210 --> 2:04:20.588
He said he knew who the Zodiac was.

2:04:20.588 --> 2:04:22.714
Gave me a name.

2:04:22.714 --> 2:04:25.000
Rick. Rick somebody.

2:04:25.000 --> 2:04:27.504
-Rick Marshall?
-Yeah.

2:04:27.504 --> 2:04:30.126
I think that the man
who you talked to called me, too.

2:04:30.126 --> 2:04:32.840
After he left, then I checked my files.

2:04:32.840 --> 2:04:34.588
I never cleared a Rick Marshall.

2:04:41.840 --> 2:04:43.000
Hello?

2:04:48.126 --> 2:04:49.882
Hello? Who is this?

2:05:00.000 --> 2:05:01.966
It's the wrong number.

2:05:07.882 --> 2:05:11.042
Does the name Rick Marshall
mean anything to you?

2:05:12.042 --> 2:05:14.168
What are you after?

2:05:14.168 --> 2:05:15.336
What do you got?

2:05:15.378 --> 2:05:19.630
Hypothetically, you just named
my favorite suspect in the whole case.

2:05:20.756 --> 2:05:22.336
This is off the record.

2:05:22.336 --> 2:05:24.756
Couple years back,
I was trying to get Marshall's prints.

2:05:24.756 --> 2:05:26.588
I handed him a photo.

2:05:26.588 --> 2:05:29.084
He looks at it. He's about to give it back
and he stops and he says,

2:05:29.084 --> 2:05:31.588
"My goodness,
I got fingerprints all over this."

2:05:31.588 --> 2:05:33.462
And he wipes them off.

2:05:34.168 --> 2:05:35.966
Why didn't you test him for handwriting?

2:05:35.966 --> 2:05:38.714
Because when they finally
did run his prints,

2:05:38.714 --> 2:05:41.084
they cleared him
against the one in Stine's cab.

2:05:41.084 --> 2:05:43.294
-So, then, it's not him.
-Maybe yes, maybe no.

2:05:43.294 --> 2:05:45.420
No. What do you mean?

2:05:45.420 --> 2:05:47.882
Zodiac left gloves behind at the scene.

2:05:47.882 --> 2:05:50.000
If he had the foresight
to bring gloves with him

2:05:50.042 --> 2:05:52.126
how the hell's he gonna
accidentally leave a print behind?

2:05:52.126 --> 2:05:54.210
But it was in the victim's blood.

2:05:54.210 --> 2:05:55.672
Could have been one of the bystanders,

2:05:55.672 --> 2:05:58.126
or a cop just reaches out,
boom, false print.

2:05:58.126 --> 2:06:00.588
Yeah, but that print
disqualified 2,500 suspects.

2:06:00.588 --> 2:06:02.000
Which is why we also used handwriting.

2:06:02.000 --> 2:06:03.420
But not for Rick Marshall.

2:06:03.420 --> 2:06:06.588
SFPD saw a handwritten sign
in the window of his house.

2:06:06.588 --> 2:06:10.504
Decided it looked nothing
like the Z letters, so they just moved on.

2:06:10.504 --> 2:06:12.840
How do they know
that Rick Marshall wrote the sign?

2:06:12.840 --> 2:06:14.126
My thoughts exactly.

2:06:15.126 --> 2:06:18.882
Rick Marshall was a Navy man.
He received code training.

2:06:18.882 --> 2:06:21.420
He was also a projectionist
at a silent film theater.

2:06:21.420 --> 2:06:23.630
Well, then, how do I get copies
of Rick Marshall's handwriting?

2:06:23.630 --> 2:06:27.588
Three ways.
One, get a warrant, which you can't.

2:06:27.588 --> 2:06:29.840
Two, get him to volunteer,
which he won't.

2:06:29.840 --> 2:06:31.840
Yeah, and three?

2:06:31.840 --> 2:06:33.588
Get creative.

2:06:33.588 --> 2:06:36.420
<i>I don't know what to tell you.</i>
<i>You get it, I’ll analyze it.</i>

2:06:36.420 --> 2:06:37.882
<i>Beyond that, you're on your own.</i>

2:06:37.882 --> 2:06:40.420
Okay, what about
the guy who came to see you,

2:06:40.420 --> 2:06:41.924
the one who called me?

2:06:41.924 --> 2:06:44.462
<i>You mean Wallace Penny?</i>

2:06:44.462 --> 2:06:46.630
Yeah. Did he leave a number?

2:06:55.924 --> 2:06:59.294
<i>-Hello?</i>
-Hi, this is Robert Graysmith.

2:06:59.294 --> 2:07:00.378
<i>How did you find me?</i>

2:07:00.378 --> 2:07:02.546
I need a sample
of Rick Marshall's handwriting.

2:07:02.546 --> 2:07:03.924
<i>I told you. Vaughn is who...</i>

2:07:03.924 --> 2:07:07.000
Mr. Penny,
if Rick Marshall is the Zodiac,

2:07:07.000 --> 2:07:09.588
I need a sample of his handwriting
to confirm it.

2:07:09.588 --> 2:07:11.210
Can you help me or not?

2:07:12.882 --> 2:07:17.630
<i>Rick used to draw movie posters</i>
<i>for the theater Vaughn worked at.</i>

2:07:17.630 --> 2:07:19.588
<i>-I’ll send one down.</i>
-Thank you.

2:07:29.546 --> 2:07:32.042
-I'll need to see more samples.
-Yeah, but is it...

2:07:32.042 --> 2:07:34.672
It's as close as I've ever seen.
We have to tread lightly here.

2:07:34.672 --> 2:07:37.210
We're talking about
implicating this man as the Zodiac.

2:07:37.210 --> 2:07:40.294
I can get more. I'll just find Vaughn
and I'll track down Linda.

2:07:40.294 --> 2:07:42.378
I mean, Linda is Darlene's sister.

2:07:42.378 --> 2:07:45.168
I've been to the DMV,
and I talked to her parents,

2:07:45.168 --> 2:07:48.378
but still, nobody knows
where to find her.

2:07:48.378 --> 2:07:52.966
Mr. Graysmith, most of the writing
matches the exemplar.

2:07:52.966 --> 2:07:56.084
In a way, though, it's the part that
doesn't match that scares me the most.

2:07:56.084 --> 2:07:58.588
-What do you mean?
-Well, on the poster,

2:07:58.588 --> 2:08:01.798
the one letter that absolutely,
positively does not match

2:08:01.798 --> 2:08:03.378
is the letter "K."

2:08:05.378 --> 2:08:09.336
You wouldn't happen to have any
animal crackers in there, would you?

2:08:09.336 --> 2:08:12.924
<i>Unit Five.</i>
<i>Toschi needs to call in on a landline.</i>

2:08:24.924 --> 2:08:27.378
<i>-Dispatch.</i>
-Hey. Dave Toschi.

2:08:27.378 --> 2:08:29.000
<i>I’ll connect you.</i>

2:08:29.924 --> 2:08:31.420
<i>-Dave?</i>
-Yeah. What's up?

2:08:31.420 --> 2:08:33.966
Jennings here from the Chronicle.

2:08:33.966 --> 2:08:35.840
It came in this morning
and you need to see it right now.

2:08:35.882 --> 2:08:37.042
See what?

2:08:37.042 --> 2:08:39.882
<i>The new Zodiac letter.</i>
<i>And it mentions you.</i>

2:08:39.882 --> 2:08:40.966
Okay, okay.

2:08:43.210 --> 2:08:45.588
Shit. All right, come on.

2:08:45.588 --> 2:08:47.630
Hall of Justice!

2:08:47.630 --> 2:08:50.714
Now! Come on, come on,
come on, come on, come on!

2:08:57.042 --> 2:08:58.126
Dave!

2:08:59.252 --> 2:09:01.210
Do you have it with you?

2:09:04.462 --> 2:09:06.756
"This is the Zodiac speaking.
I'm back with you.

2:09:06.756 --> 2:09:09.924
"Tell Herb Caen I am here,
I have always been here.

2:09:09.924 --> 2:09:13.042
"That city pig Toschi is good,
but I am smarter and better.

2:09:13.042 --> 2:09:16.042
"He will get tired, then leave me alone.

2:09:16.042 --> 2:09:19.420
"I'm waiting for a good movie about me.
Who will play me?

2:09:19.420 --> 2:09:21.630
"I'm now in control of all things."

2:09:21.630 --> 2:09:24.336
These guys are from Internal Affairs.

2:09:26.126 --> 2:09:27.840
We need to talk.

2:09:27.840 --> 2:09:29.714
<i>Good evening. Our top story tonight,</i>

2:09:29.714 --> 2:09:32.294
<i>the San Francisco Police Department</i>
<i>has confirmed</i>

2:09:32.294 --> 2:09:34.924
<i>that the man</i>
<i>who calls himself the Zodiac</i>

2:09:34.924 --> 2:09:39.378
<i>and terrorized the Bay Area</i>
<i>has broken his silence of 51 months.</i>

2:09:39.378 --> 2:09:42.126
<i>In a letter claiming,</i>
<i>"I am back with you,"</i>

2:09:42.126 --> 2:09:45.882
<i>the Zodiac makes no overt threats</i>
<i>against the citizenry,</i>

2:09:45.882 --> 2:09:48.798
<i>and muses that his life and times</i>
<i>would make the best movie script yet.</i>

2:09:48.798 --> 2:09:50.378
These carrots are perfect.

2:09:50.378 --> 2:09:51.882
<i>The terse 66 word message</i>
<i>also manages...</i>

2:09:51.882 --> 2:09:53.000
Just go.

2:09:53.000 --> 2:09:56.084
...to mention San Francisco Chronicle
<i>columnist Herb Caen</i>

2:09:56.084 --> 2:09:59.084
<i>and the Department's own</i>
<i>David Toschi by name.</i>

2:09:59.126 --> 2:10:00.798
-May I be excused?
<i>-Are they targets?</i>

2:10:00.798 --> 2:10:01.924
Fine, but you have to come back

2:10:01.924 --> 2:10:03.630
and finish at least half
of what's on that plate.

2:10:03.630 --> 2:10:04.840
<i>More team coverage</i>
<i>on the cipher slayer's return...</i>

2:10:04.840 --> 2:10:05.966
-Okay?
-Okay.

2:10:05.966 --> 2:10:08.504
<i>...begins as Alan Freeman has more.</i>

2:10:08.504 --> 2:10:09.756
<i>Thank you, Eric.</i>

2:10:09.756 --> 2:10:12.336
San Francisco Chronicle columnist
<i>Armistead Maupin says</i>

2:10:12.336 --> 2:10:15.000
<i>that he thinks not only</i>
<i>is this new letter a forgery,</i>

2:10:15.000 --> 2:10:17.042
<i>but it was written by the very man</i>

2:10:17.042 --> 2:10:20.882
<i>trusted to hunt down this killer,</i>
<i>David Toschi.</i>

2:10:20.882 --> 2:10:24.672
<i>Maupin, a very well-respected author,</i>
<i>has gone on record saying</i>

2:10:24.672 --> 2:10:29.378
<i>that he believes Toschi wrote the letter</i>
<i>to drum up publicity for himself.</i>

2:10:29.378 --> 2:10:32.546
Maupin used David
as a character in his column.

2:10:32.546 --> 2:10:34.546
David got a kick out of it

2:10:34.546 --> 2:10:36.630
and so he wrote
a couple of anonymous letters

2:10:36.630 --> 2:10:38.630
asking for the character
to be brought back.

2:10:38.630 --> 2:10:41.756
<i>It was like</i>
<i>writing fan mail to himself. That's all.</i>

2:10:41.756 --> 2:10:44.042
<i>But David did not write that letter.</i>

2:10:44.042 --> 2:10:47.294
No, I'm sure that he didn't.
And I'm sure that this will all blow over.

2:10:47.294 --> 2:10:48.714
<i>Blow over?</i>

2:10:48.714 --> 2:10:51.042
They kicked him out of Homicide.

2:10:51.042 --> 2:10:54.378
They made him give his handwriting
like some common criminal.

2:10:54.378 --> 2:10:56.756
-May I talk to him?
<i>-No.</i>

2:10:57.798 --> 2:10:59.084
Okay, can you just ask him

2:10:59.084 --> 2:11:01.546
if he ever investigated
a man named Rick Marshall?

2:11:01.546 --> 2:11:03.420
Is that all you can think about?

2:11:03.420 --> 2:11:06.840
Mr. Graysmith,
Maupin works at your paper. We trust...

2:11:12.630 --> 2:11:14.084
This girl, she wants music lessons?

2:11:14.084 --> 2:11:15.588
Dave! Dave!

2:11:18.042 --> 2:11:20.336
I'll catch up to you.

2:11:20.336 --> 2:11:22.672
You stop calling my house.
Do you understand me?

2:11:22.672 --> 2:11:24.462
I just need your help to find Linda.

2:11:24.462 --> 2:11:26.504
-Jesus.
-Look, two seconds.

2:11:28.462 --> 2:11:30.966
Look, we've been
running handwriting samples.

2:11:30.966 --> 2:11:33.294
-Who's we?
-Sherwood and I.

2:11:33.294 --> 2:11:34.504
Sherwood?

2:11:34.504 --> 2:11:36.714
Sherwood who was fired
from Questioned Documents?

2:11:36.714 --> 2:11:38.378
Sherwood who drinks
like Paul Avery now?

2:11:38.378 --> 2:11:40.966
-He retired.
-Is that what he told you?

2:11:40.966 --> 2:11:45.168
-What, are you saying he's wrong?
-I'm saying stop calling my house.

2:11:45.756 --> 2:11:47.378
-We ran them on Rick Marshall.
-No, Robert.

2:11:47.378 --> 2:11:48.798
No, I know you don't think it's him.

2:11:48.798 --> 2:11:50.336
I mean, no, I am not having
this conversation.

2:11:50.336 --> 2:11:53.252
But I think that Marshall knew Darlene,
and I can't talk to Mageau or Linda,

2:11:53.252 --> 2:11:54.336
so I'm gonna talk to Bob Vaughn.

2:11:54.336 --> 2:11:55.672
-Robert. Robert, stop it!
-What?

2:11:55.672 --> 2:11:58.042
Okay, the Rick Marshalls
of this world will suck you dry.

2:11:58.042 --> 2:11:59.084
They're blind alleys.

2:11:59.084 --> 2:12:01.672
But he said he wasn't gonna announce
his murders anymore, Dave.

2:12:01.672 --> 2:12:02.840
He was just gonna do them.

2:12:02.840 --> 2:12:05.882
Do you know what the chances
of us arresting someone are now?

2:12:05.882 --> 2:12:10.084
Too much time has gone by, okay?
Too much of the evidence is lost.

2:12:10.084 --> 2:12:13.336
People get old, Robert. They forget.

2:12:13.336 --> 2:12:17.588
Now, I have been a cop for 25 years.
Murder police for 12.

2:12:17.588 --> 2:12:19.966
-What do you do for a living?
-You know what I do for a living.

2:12:19.966 --> 2:12:22.294
-You're a cartoonist.
-So what are you saying?

2:12:22.336 --> 2:12:25.462
I am saying Zodiac was my job.
It is not yours.

2:12:28.672 --> 2:12:31.126
-He's still out there, Dave.
-No, Robert. I am through with this.

2:12:31.126 --> 2:12:33.042
I am through with you.

2:12:39.336 --> 2:12:41.924
What about September 26, 1970?

2:12:41.924 --> 2:12:45.504
-Okay, which one was that?
-The Lake Tahoe nurse goes missing.

2:12:48.462 --> 2:12:49.924
One day before the vernal equinox.

2:12:49.924 --> 2:12:51.924
-Dad?
-Yeah. Mark that.

2:12:51.924 --> 2:12:55.672
Got another one. June 19th, 1971.

2:12:55.672 --> 2:12:58.462
That's got to be
near the summer solstice.

2:13:00.798 --> 2:13:02.168
Oh, guys.

2:13:02.168 --> 2:13:05.210
Don't tell Mom about
our special project, okay?

2:13:05.714 --> 2:13:09.336
How come you and Mom
don't sleep in the same bed anymore?

2:13:12.924 --> 2:13:13.966
Hello.

2:13:13.966 --> 2:13:16.126
<i>Mr. Graysmith,</i>
<i>it's Ken Narlow from Napa.</i>

2:13:16.126 --> 2:13:20.504
Oh, Captain Narlow.
Thank you for calling me back.

2:13:20.504 --> 2:13:22.462
<i>Yeah. How can I help?</i>

2:13:22.462 --> 2:13:25.252
I called you because we've been
cross-referencing lunar cycles

2:13:25.252 --> 2:13:27.000
with the Zodiac's timeline.

2:13:27.000 --> 2:13:31.336
More often than not, each cycle
since '69 corresponds with an attack

2:13:31.336 --> 2:13:34.294
or with one of the letters,
or an unsolved homicide.

2:13:34.294 --> 2:13:37.210
<i>-Who's working with you on this?</i>
-Some colleagues.

2:13:37.210 --> 2:13:38.294
Dad?

2:13:39.588 --> 2:13:42.126
-Ken, can you hold on one second?
-Dad?

2:13:42.126 --> 2:13:44.168
-What is it?
-What's this?

2:13:48.000 --> 2:13:51.168
<i>In the decade since the Zodiac's</i>
<i>last cipher was received,</i>

2:13:51.168 --> 2:13:54.756
<i>every federal agency</i>
<i>has taken a crack at decoding it.</i>

2:13:54.756 --> 2:13:57.630
<i>But today,</i>
<i>where those agencies had failed,</i>

2:13:57.630 --> 2:14:00.336
<i>a cartoonist has succeeded.</i>

2:14:00.336 --> 2:14:02.000
<i>How did you do it?</i>

2:14:02.000 --> 2:14:07.420
<i>Oh, just a lot of books from the library,</i>
<i>and I love puzzles, so I just...</i>

2:14:09.504 --> 2:14:11.798
Yeah. The fucking library.

2:14:11.798 --> 2:14:14.966
<i>I believe that you can accomplish</i>
<i>anything that you put your mind...</i>

2:14:17.840 --> 2:14:20.630
That's a "J"? Okay. Honor Camp?

2:14:22.252 --> 2:14:23.882
Thank you so much.

2:14:25.882 --> 2:14:28.210
Hey, we found Linda.
She's in jail. Isn't that great?

2:14:28.210 --> 2:14:29.462
Why'd you do it?

2:14:29.462 --> 2:14:30.966
Because she'll be able to identify Rick...

2:14:30.966 --> 2:14:33.714
-What are you talking about?
-You went on TV.

2:14:34.294 --> 2:14:36.042
You put yourself out there
for him to see.

2:14:36.042 --> 2:14:37.672
Oh, hon, you're being paranoid.

2:14:37.672 --> 2:14:39.756
Oh, hon, you're being paranoid.

2:14:39.756 --> 2:14:40.840
The who's been calling our house
in the middle of the night?

2:14:40.840 --> 2:14:42.042
Nobody.

2:14:44.042 --> 2:14:45.798
What's it gonna take
for you to be done with this?

2:14:45.798 --> 2:14:48.798
I can't talk about this now.
I have to go see Bob Vaughn.

2:14:48.798 --> 2:14:52.252
Well, that's too bad,
because we're gonna talk about this.

2:14:52.252 --> 2:14:54.672
And when is it gonna be finished?

2:14:54.672 --> 2:14:56.588
When you catch him?
When you arrest him?

2:14:56.588 --> 2:14:58.840
-Be serious.
-I am serious.

2:15:00.630 --> 2:15:04.210
I need to know who he is.

2:15:04.210 --> 2:15:07.462
I need to stand there,

2:15:07.462 --> 2:15:11.378
I need to look him in the eye
and I need to know that it's him.

2:15:13.252 --> 2:15:15.630
Is that more important
than your family's safety?

2:15:15.630 --> 2:15:17.126
Of course not.

2:15:19.084 --> 2:15:21.504
Why? Why do you need to do this?

2:15:23.378 --> 2:15:24.462
Why?

2:15:26.420 --> 2:15:28.504
Because nobody else will.

2:15:28.504 --> 2:15:30.546
That's not good enough.

2:15:30.546 --> 2:15:32.420
Are you done? Can I go?

2:15:47.714 --> 2:15:49.840
-Mr. Vaughn?
-Mr. Graysmith?

2:15:49.882 --> 2:15:51.000
-Yes.
-Hi.

2:15:51.000 --> 2:15:52.420
You needed to speak to me?

2:15:52.420 --> 2:15:54.924
Yes. There's a coffee shop
right on the corner.

2:15:54.924 --> 2:15:58.084
-Why don't we just go to my home?
-Oh, I don't wanna put you out.

2:15:58.084 --> 2:16:00.084
It's no trouble at all.

2:16:00.084 --> 2:16:02.672
-Where are you parked?
-Just right there.

2:16:02.672 --> 2:16:06.042
-You can follow me.
-Oh. Okay.

2:16:24.714 --> 2:16:26.336
Watch your step.

2:16:27.798 --> 2:16:29.504
Come in.

2:16:30.882 --> 2:16:34.084
-Very nice house.
-Oh, thank you.

2:16:34.084 --> 2:16:36.042
It's very rustic.

2:16:36.042 --> 2:16:39.294
-Can I take your jacket?
-No, thank you, I'm fine.

2:16:39.294 --> 2:16:41.294
Okay. This way, please.

2:16:44.084 --> 2:16:45.924
-Have a seat.
-Thank you.

2:16:45.924 --> 2:16:48.546
-How about some tea?
-Oh, no, I'm all right.

2:16:48.546 --> 2:16:50.000
-You sure?
-Yes.

2:16:50.882 --> 2:16:54.714
I wanted to ask you about a film
that the Avenue may have played

2:16:54.714 --> 2:16:56.714
while you were the organist there.

2:16:56.714 --> 2:16:59.084
<i>The Most Dangerous Game?</i>

2:16:59.084 --> 2:17:02.546
Oh, it's a classic. R KO. 1932.

2:17:02.546 --> 2:17:07.336
Fay Wray, Joel McCrea, Leslie Banks.
We've run that picture many times.

2:17:07.336 --> 2:17:08.882
In '68, '69?

2:17:10.462 --> 2:17:12.756
I'd have to check my records. Why?

2:17:12.756 --> 2:17:14.882
Do you remember the Zodiac?

2:17:17.084 --> 2:17:19.462
This is about Rick Marshall, isn't it?

2:17:19.462 --> 2:17:22.966
-He was a projectionist there, right?
-For a time, yes.

2:17:22.966 --> 2:17:27.084
But I have no occasion
to correspond with him these days.

2:17:27.084 --> 2:17:29.672
Okay. Well, there is a connection

2:17:29.672 --> 2:17:32.546
between one of the Zodiac attacks
and that film.

2:17:32.546 --> 2:17:34.294
You mean the symbol?

2:17:35.546 --> 2:17:36.756
Hold on.

2:17:37.294 --> 2:17:41.420
The Zodiac symbol on film.
It's on the countdown.

2:17:45.294 --> 2:17:48.000
It's trimmed off each reel
before it's shown,

2:17:48.000 --> 2:17:50.630
but it always arrives with it.

2:17:50.630 --> 2:17:52.042
Right there.

2:17:52.630 --> 2:17:56.336
The first time I saw it in the papers,
I thought about that.

2:17:57.168 --> 2:17:58.840
We got a tip

2:17:58.840 --> 2:18:02.882
that Rick left a film canister here
that he told you never to open.

2:18:02.882 --> 2:18:06.000
A tip about a mysterious film canister?

2:18:06.882 --> 2:18:08.210
Is it true?

2:18:10.126 --> 2:18:11.336
Yes.

2:18:12.000 --> 2:18:14.420
-Did you open it?
-No.

2:18:14.420 --> 2:18:18.714
-May I see it?
-Rick took it back in 1972.

2:18:20.420 --> 2:18:25.294
This tip is how you got it in your head
that Rick is the Zodiac?

2:18:25.294 --> 2:18:27.042
That and the poster.

2:18:27.042 --> 2:18:28.420
The poster?

2:18:30.336 --> 2:18:32.210
The poster that Rick drew.

2:18:32.210 --> 2:18:35.504
The handwriting is the closest
that we have ever come to a match.

2:18:35.504 --> 2:18:38.882
-Rick didn't draw any posters.
-No, he drew this one.

2:18:38.882 --> 2:18:42.336
Mr. Graysmith, I do the posters myself.

2:18:43.714 --> 2:18:45.588
That's my handwriting.

2:18:53.840 --> 2:18:56.798
I won't take any more of your time.

2:18:56.798 --> 2:19:02.294
Why don't I just go and find out
when we played that film?

2:19:02.294 --> 2:19:03.840
Oh, that's all right.

2:19:03.840 --> 2:19:07.294
It's not a problem.
They're just down in the basement.

2:19:09.084 --> 2:19:12.042
Not many people
have basements in California.

2:19:14.714 --> 2:19:15.798
I do.

2:19:17.966 --> 2:19:19.966
You coming, Mr. Graysmith?

2:19:31.252 --> 2:19:34.966
The original studio one-sheets,
I always kept for myself.

2:19:36.840 --> 2:19:39.462
The cheapo knock-offs
like you brought today

2:19:39.462 --> 2:19:42.588
I end up tossing into the back alley.

2:19:57.084 --> 2:19:58.588
'69.

2:20:04.294 --> 2:20:05.630
You live alone?

2:20:05.630 --> 2:20:11.504
Most Dangerous Game ran in May '69.

2:20:11.504 --> 2:20:13.966
So, that would be about

2:20:14.840 --> 2:20:18.168
nine weeks before
the first Zodiac letter, correct?

2:20:21.042 --> 2:20:22.168
Yeah.

2:20:26.630 --> 2:20:30.924
Do you think he saw the film
in our theater and was inspired?

2:20:37.000 --> 2:20:39.924
Are you sure
there's nobody else in the house?

2:20:41.504 --> 2:20:44.210
Would you like
to go upstairs and check?

2:20:44.924 --> 2:20:45.966
No.

2:20:49.042 --> 2:20:51.630
Thank you. Thanks for everything.

2:20:52.462 --> 2:20:53.966
You're welcome.

2:21:15.210 --> 2:21:16.630
It's locked.

2:21:27.462 --> 2:21:28.798
Thank you.

2:21:31.924 --> 2:21:33.924
Good night, Mr. Graysmith!

2:21:53.840 --> 2:21:57.546
Two killers. Got to be two killers.
One has the...

2:22:05.420 --> 2:22:06.588
Guys?

2:22:40.126 --> 2:22:42.084
You've got five minutes.

2:22:50.252 --> 2:22:51.420
Linda?

2:22:52.546 --> 2:22:54.042
Hi, I'm Robert.

2:22:58.000 --> 2:22:59.756
Did you get my note?

2:23:00.672 --> 2:23:02.672
-What's this about?
-Zodiac.

2:23:04.210 --> 2:23:05.462
Figures.

2:23:06.798 --> 2:23:09.630
-You got the look.
-What look?

2:23:09.630 --> 2:23:11.672
I didn't mean anything.

2:23:12.924 --> 2:23:15.294
Tell me about this painting party.

2:23:16.462 --> 2:23:19.084
I told the cops about that so long ago.

2:23:22.546 --> 2:23:24.420
Darlene always had
a lot of boys around,

2:23:24.420 --> 2:23:26.462
even though she was married.

2:23:26.462 --> 2:23:28.546
And this one guy was weird, though.

2:23:28.546 --> 2:23:31.924
He used to bring her presents
from Tijuana and...

2:23:33.126 --> 2:23:35.840
I don't know why
she was friends with him.

2:23:35.840 --> 2:23:38.378
She once told me he'd killed somebody.

2:23:38.378 --> 2:23:40.042
Really?

2:23:40.042 --> 2:23:42.378
Yeah, I think maybe
when he was in the service.

2:23:42.378 --> 2:23:44.420
-Navy?
-I think so.

2:23:44.420 --> 2:23:46.714
Was he into movies?
Was he a movie buff?

2:23:46.714 --> 2:23:49.714
I can tell you that
he was not into people.

2:23:49.714 --> 2:23:51.126
The party Darlene threw,

2:23:51.126 --> 2:23:54.126
people were supposed to
just show up and drink beer, help paint.

2:23:54.126 --> 2:23:56.462
But this guy showed up in a suit,

2:23:56.462 --> 2:23:59.504
and just sat in a chair
all by himself all night long.

2:23:59.504 --> 2:24:01.042
Didn't talk to anyone.

2:24:01.042 --> 2:24:03.000
And Darlene told me
to stay away from him.

2:24:03.000 --> 2:24:04.840
She was scared of him.

2:24:07.084 --> 2:24:09.672
And a couple of weeks later,
she was dead.

2:24:09.672 --> 2:24:12.126
I'm sorry. Do you remember his name?

2:24:13.126 --> 2:24:17.084
I mean, it was short,
like a nickname, like Stan.

2:24:17.084 --> 2:24:19.420
-Rick?
-No, I don't think so.

2:24:20.294 --> 2:24:22.588
-Are you sure?
-Yeah.

2:24:22.588 --> 2:24:25.252
How can you be sure?
It was a long time ago. Think hard.

2:24:25.252 --> 2:24:27.378
I am thinking hard.

2:24:27.378 --> 2:24:28.798
It was Rick.

2:24:29.798 --> 2:24:30.966
No, it wasn't.

2:24:30.966 --> 2:24:33.462
-It was Rick. It was Rick Marshall.
-No.

2:24:33.462 --> 2:24:35.252
Just say it!

2:24:35.252 --> 2:24:37.126
It wasn't Rick.

2:24:49.882 --> 2:24:51.210
It was Leigh.

2:24:54.378 --> 2:24:56.924
-Leigh?
-Yeah, Leigh.

2:24:58.252 --> 2:24:59.588
Sounds right.

2:25:04.378 --> 2:25:07.294
Officer! I need you to let me in.

2:25:07.294 --> 2:25:09.546
-Is this an emergency?
-No, I just need to see one file.

2:25:09.546 --> 2:25:11.294
No, you need to come back
tomorrow morning.

2:25:11.294 --> 2:25:13.588
-One file, just for one second.
-8:00 a.m. , when we're open.

2:25:13.588 --> 2:25:15.336
Sergeant! Sergeant Mulanax!

2:25:15.336 --> 2:25:17.882
Sergeant, I just need to see one file!

2:25:17.882 --> 2:25:21.294
Just give me five minutes.
I know exactly where it is.

2:25:22.252 --> 2:25:23.462
Please!

2:25:36.798 --> 2:25:38.588
I shouldn't be talking to you.

2:25:38.588 --> 2:25:40.588
-You got five minutes.
-Okay.

2:25:42.840 --> 2:25:44.168
Here. Here.

2:25:44.168 --> 2:25:48.042
Linda states that some of
Darlene's closest friends are Leigh,

2:25:48.042 --> 2:25:51.126
who used to bring Darlene
presents from Tijuana.

2:25:51.126 --> 2:25:53.126
-So what?
-He knew her.

2:25:53.126 --> 2:25:54.924
Linda said Leigh. This is Leigh.

2:25:54.924 --> 2:25:57.462
No. That's just one name in a file
that contains hundreds.

2:25:57.462 --> 2:25:58.924
It's nothing.

2:25:59.672 --> 2:26:01.882
-Dave Toschi...
-Agrees with me.

2:26:02.378 --> 2:26:05.252
Our investigation
into this subject is over.

2:26:08.252 --> 2:26:09.546
I'm sorry.

2:26:18.672 --> 2:26:19.840
Hello.

2:26:35.000 --> 2:26:36.420
Who's there?

2:26:39.882 --> 2:26:43.462
-You didn't return my calls.
-Oh, I've been kind of busy.

2:26:43.462 --> 2:26:45.336
Yeah. I can see that.

2:26:47.546 --> 2:26:49.420
How's the book coming?

2:26:52.462 --> 2:26:54.462
I tried to send you these.

2:26:55.546 --> 2:26:57.420
I called the Chron.

2:26:57.420 --> 2:27:00.210
Well, I'm not a cartoonist anymore, so...

2:27:01.756 --> 2:27:03.000
I heard.

2:27:08.126 --> 2:27:10.756
When's the last time
you ate something?

2:27:13.252 --> 2:27:15.420
Nothing makes sense anymore.

2:27:18.084 --> 2:27:20.378
-Did it ever?
-Yeah, it did.

2:27:21.840 --> 2:27:24.798
Robert, it was just the date
that didn't end.

2:27:25.252 --> 2:27:27.042
You don't mean that.

2:27:28.462 --> 2:27:29.672
A little.

2:27:32.546 --> 2:27:34.420
The kids miss you.

2:27:34.420 --> 2:27:37.546
-I can't have them see me like this.
-Neither can I.

2:27:38.294 --> 2:27:40.420
So, do whatever you have to,

2:27:41.378 --> 2:27:42.924
but finish this.

2:28:10.462 --> 2:28:11.546
Dave!

2:28:12.420 --> 2:28:14.042
Dave! It's Robert!

2:28:16.210 --> 2:28:17.924
-Dave!
-Is he actually here?

2:28:17.924 --> 2:28:19.672
I'm gonna kill him.

2:28:20.000 --> 2:28:22.630
I'm calling SFPD. Where's my gun?

2:28:25.168 --> 2:28:26.420
Dave!

2:28:26.420 --> 2:28:28.252
Robert! Go away!

2:28:28.252 --> 2:28:30.336
Dave! He made a mistake!

2:28:30.336 --> 2:28:32.378
-Get away from the window.
-I'll meet you around front.

2:28:32.378 --> 2:28:33.882
No, you won't.

2:28:35.000 --> 2:28:37.336
-You have to hear this!
-No, I don't, Robert!

2:28:37.336 --> 2:28:39.882
The birthday was the one time
that he was weak!

2:28:39.882 --> 2:28:41.798
The one time
that he gave something away!

2:28:41.798 --> 2:28:45.126
-Robert, I am calling the police.
-It's Arthur Leigh Allen!

2:28:50.126 --> 2:28:52.504
Where did you get that name?

2:28:52.504 --> 2:28:54.126
He called the Bellis' house.

2:28:54.126 --> 2:28:56.462
December '69.
"I need to kill. Today's my birthday."

2:28:56.462 --> 2:28:58.546
It was his birthday.

2:28:58.546 --> 2:29:01.462
Arthur Leigh Allen
was born on December 18th.

2:29:04.504 --> 2:29:05.924
Get in here.

2:29:08.000 --> 2:29:10.210
-Here you go.
-Thanks.

2:29:13.168 --> 2:29:15.042
He wrote me, you know?

2:29:15.714 --> 2:29:16.924
2,500 suspects,

2:29:16.924 --> 2:29:20.546
the only one who ever wrote me
a letter was Leigh Allen.

2:29:21.420 --> 2:29:23.252
They like to help, you know, sometimes.

2:29:23.252 --> 2:29:25.042
Yes, Robert, I know.

2:29:26.126 --> 2:29:28.966
He was arrested January 1975
for molestation.

2:29:28.966 --> 2:29:30.966
He sent me that when he got out.

2:29:30.966 --> 2:29:33.798
"Dear Dave, if I can ever be
of any help to you, just let me know.

2:29:33.798 --> 2:29:35.714
"I'm sorry I wasn't your man."

2:29:35.714 --> 2:29:37.378
And it's typewritten.

2:29:37.378 --> 2:29:39.798
Using a typewriter is not a crime.

2:29:41.210 --> 2:29:43.000
And he knew Darlene.

2:29:44.378 --> 2:29:46.420
It's in the Vallejo files.

2:29:51.588 --> 2:29:55.042
Mulanax said that
he was your favorite suspect.

2:29:55.042 --> 2:29:59.042
That you spent two years on him,
and that nobody ever came close.

2:30:02.084 --> 2:30:04.084
All the evidence said no.

2:30:05.336 --> 2:30:07.672
Sherwood disqualified his handwriting.

2:30:07.672 --> 2:30:10.840
The same Sherwood
that drinks like Paul Avery now?

2:30:11.714 --> 2:30:13.756
Yes, you have Sherwood Morrill
in writing saying,

2:30:13.756 --> 2:30:14.882
"I'm sorry, this just won't work."

2:30:14.882 --> 2:30:16.756
-But you also have Terry Pascoe...
-His protégé.

2:30:16.756 --> 2:30:17.882
Yeah, fine, it's his protégé,

2:30:17.882 --> 2:30:19.840
but he's a handwriting expert
nonetheless, and he's saying,

2:30:19.840 --> 2:30:22.630
"Do not disqualify this suspect
on the basis of handwriting."

2:30:22.630 --> 2:30:24.672
-So the two cancel each other out.
-No, they don't.

2:30:24.672 --> 2:30:26.042
It was Sherwood's case.

2:30:26.084 --> 2:30:27.630
He was the head
of Questioned Documents.

2:30:27.630 --> 2:30:29.084
If it went to trial,

2:30:29.084 --> 2:30:32.126
all the defense would have to do
is call Sherwood to the stand.

2:30:32.126 --> 2:30:34.882
And there was no way of getting Allen
into court in the first place,

2:30:34.882 --> 2:30:36.210
because there was no evidence, Robert.

2:30:36.210 --> 2:30:37.462
What do you mean,
there's no evidence?

2:30:37.462 --> 2:30:38.672
You have him seen with the ciphers.

2:30:38.672 --> 2:30:41.000
The military boot prints.
The same size shoes and gloves.

2:30:41.000 --> 2:30:43.294
<i>The Most Dangerous Game.</i>
The Zodiac watch.

2:30:43.336 --> 2:30:44.630
The background with school children.

2:30:44.630 --> 2:30:46.546
The misspellings of Christ-mass.
The bloody knives.

2:30:46.546 --> 2:30:48.504
All circumstantial.

2:30:48.504 --> 2:30:51.378
Paul Stine's shirt, his wallet, his keys.

2:30:51.378 --> 2:30:53.210
We should have found
one of those things in that trailer.

2:30:53.210 --> 2:30:54.966
-We didn't.
-That's...

2:30:57.378 --> 2:30:59.462
Okay. Catherine Allen states that

2:30:59.462 --> 2:31:01.714
"Leigh cleaned out his trailer
on Friday after work

2:31:01.714 --> 2:31:05.462
"and moved it to Santa Rosa
on Saturday, August 7th, 1971."

2:31:05.462 --> 2:31:07.588
You interviewed him
at the refinery on August 4th.

2:31:07.588 --> 2:31:09.210
-Yeah.
-So, he's cleaning out his trailer,

2:31:09.210 --> 2:31:13.084
he's moving into a different county
48 hours after you interviewed him?

2:31:14.630 --> 2:31:17.756
Okay. Okay.
Look at the stuff side by side, Dave.

2:31:17.756 --> 2:31:18.966
All right.

2:31:18.966 --> 2:31:21.840
Okay, Arthur Leigh Allen
and the Zodiac, their timelines.

2:31:21.840 --> 2:31:24.630
-When was the first murder in Vallejo?
-Christmas, 1968.

2:31:24.630 --> 2:31:27.336
Eight months before that,
Allen is fired for molesting his students

2:31:27.336 --> 2:31:29.546
and his family discovers
that he's a pedophile.

2:31:29.546 --> 2:31:31.924
-Now, when do the letters begin?
-July, '69.

2:31:31.924 --> 2:31:33.714
After the murder of Darlene Ferrin.

2:31:33.714 --> 2:31:36.882
And they continue
until you go to see him at work.

2:31:36.882 --> 2:31:40.210
Now, after that, do any of the letters
contain swatches of Paul Stine's shirt?

2:31:40.210 --> 2:31:42.126
No. Because he dumped them,
because he got scared.

2:31:42.126 --> 2:31:43.966
Because he knew
that you were on to him.

2:31:43.966 --> 2:31:47.798
-So, when's the next letter from Zodiac?
-Not until January of 1974.

2:31:47.798 --> 2:31:49.294
He is silent for three years.

2:31:49.294 --> 2:31:51.168
Then, in '74, he feels comfortable again

2:31:51.168 --> 2:31:53.168
because everybody's moved off
Allen as a suspect.

2:31:53.168 --> 2:31:54.252
And what do we get?

2:31:54.252 --> 2:31:58.378
Three new letters from Zodiac
in January, May, and July in '74.

2:31:58.378 --> 2:32:01.504
-But then the letters stop.
-What happens to Allen?

2:32:05.000 --> 2:32:06.504
He's arrested.

2:32:07.420 --> 2:32:10.840
January, 1975,
they send him to Atascadero.

2:32:10.840 --> 2:32:13.840
We don't get another letter from Zodiac
the entire time he's there.

2:32:13.840 --> 2:32:16.588
-When is he released?
-August, '77.

2:32:16.588 --> 2:32:20.420
Allen gets out. He types you an apology,
and then what?

2:32:20.420 --> 2:32:23.630
We get our first new Zodiac letter
in four years.

2:32:29.210 --> 2:32:32.714
Okay. Zodiac had to have known
Darlene Ferrin, right?

2:32:32.714 --> 2:32:35.042
Yes, because of the phone calls
on the night of her murder.

2:32:35.042 --> 2:32:37.924
Because of the Vallejo file,

2:32:37.924 --> 2:32:40.042
we know that Darlene knew
a man named Leigh?

2:32:40.042 --> 2:32:41.126
Yes.

2:32:41.126 --> 2:32:43.000
So, all coincidence aside, Robert,

2:32:43.000 --> 2:32:45.924
how can you be sure that Leigh Allen
is the Leigh from this file?

2:32:45.924 --> 2:32:48.462
Now, Vallejo is a small town,
but it's not that small.

2:32:48.462 --> 2:32:49.882
How do you put
the two of them together?

2:32:49.882 --> 2:32:53.126
This is a case that's covered
both Northern and Southern California,

2:32:53.126 --> 2:32:55.630
with victims and suspects
spread over hundreds of miles.

2:32:55.630 --> 2:32:57.378
-Would you agree?
-Yes.

2:32:58.630 --> 2:33:01.504
Darlene Ferrin worked
at the Vallejo House of Pancakes

2:33:01.504 --> 2:33:04.042
on the corner of Tennessee and Caroll.

2:33:06.882 --> 2:33:11.630
Arthur Leigh Allen lived in his
mother's basement on Fresno Street.

2:33:13.336 --> 2:33:16.756
Door to door, that is less than 50 yards.

2:33:20.126 --> 2:33:21.630
Is that true?

2:33:22.630 --> 2:33:24.168
I've walked it.

2:33:27.966 --> 2:33:29.462
Jesus Christ.

2:33:36.126 --> 2:33:37.126
So?

2:33:41.042 --> 2:33:42.714
The prints, the handwriting...

2:33:42.714 --> 2:33:45.714
-I'm not asking you as a cop.
-But I am a cop.

2:33:48.588 --> 2:33:50.714
I can't prove this.

2:33:50.714 --> 2:33:53.756
Just because you can't prove it,
doesn't mean it's not true.

2:33:53.756 --> 2:33:55.420
Easy, Dirty Harry.

2:33:58.966 --> 2:34:00.546
Finish the book.

2:34:09.462 --> 2:34:11.966
Thank you. Thank you for breakfast.

2:35:20.210 --> 2:35:21.714
Can I help you?

2:35:23.378 --> 2:35:24.378
No.

2:36:45.756 --> 2:36:47.126
Mr. Mageau.

2:36:47.798 --> 2:36:50.168
Thanks for coming to see me.

2:36:50.168 --> 2:36:51.630
You're the one I talked to on the phone?

2:36:51.630 --> 2:36:55.168
I'm George Bawart. Vallejo PD.
I took over for Jack Mulanax.

2:36:56.168 --> 2:36:59.252
It's been 22 years.
I don't know how I can help you.

2:36:59.252 --> 2:37:00.546
Well, this is just a formality.

2:37:00.546 --> 2:37:02.042
I'm gonna show you
a group of photographs.

2:37:02.042 --> 2:37:04.000
Now, the person that shot you
may or may not be

2:37:04.000 --> 2:37:06.126
among these photographs.

2:37:06.126 --> 2:37:07.420
You don't have to pick anybody out

2:37:07.420 --> 2:37:09.714
just because I'm showing you
these pictures, you understand?

2:37:09.714 --> 2:37:11.252
Yes, sir, I do.

2:37:12.126 --> 2:37:13.504
All right.

2:37:14.504 --> 2:37:16.042
Take your time.

2:37:16.504 --> 2:37:19.336
If you don't recognize anyone,
that's okay.

2:37:30.798 --> 2:37:32.168
That's him.

2:37:33.630 --> 2:37:35.672
How sure are you?

2:37:35.672 --> 2:37:37.546
Yeah, I'm pretty sure.

2:37:40.210 --> 2:37:41.420
He had a round face like this guy.

2:37:41.420 --> 2:37:42.756
Wait. Am I to understand

2:37:42.756 --> 2:37:44.588
that you're now identifying
the second photograph?

2:37:44.588 --> 2:37:47.714
No, no. Just that
he had a round face like that.

2:37:49.756 --> 2:37:51.252
It's this man.

2:37:52.126 --> 2:37:53.462
All right.

2:37:55.294 --> 2:37:58.378
Now, on a scale of one to 10,
10 being positive,

2:38:02.462 --> 2:38:04.084
how sure are you?

2:38:07.840 --> 2:38:09.504
At least an eight.

2:38:12.252 --> 2:38:16.126
The last time I saw this face
was July 4th, 1969.

2:38:19.378 --> 2:38:22.084
I am very sure
that's the man who shot me.
